Networking Devices & Their OSI Layer

Below is the most accurate mapping used in networking (Cisco/CompTIA standard).

1. Hub

OSI Layer: Layer 1 – Physical

What it does:
Sends incoming data to all ports
No filtering
No understanding of MAC/IP addresses
Very outdated

Key point: Works with bits only.
--------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Repeater

OSI Layer: Layer 1 – Physical

What it does:
Amplifies and regenerates signals
Extends cable distance
Key point: Boosts weak signals, no filtering.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Bridge

OSI Layer: Layer 2 – Data Link

What it does:
Divides network into segments
Uses MAC addresses
Reduces collisions
Key point: Smarter than a hub.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Switch (most important Layer 2 device)

OSI Layer: Layer 2 – Data Link

What it does:
Forwards frames based on MAC address table (CAM table)
Creates separate collision domains
Supports VLANs
Faster and more secure than hubs

Note:
Some switches operate at Layer 3 too (called Layer-3 switches / multilayer switches).
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Router
OSI Layer: Layer 3 – Network

What it does:
Uses IP addresses
Performs routing (path selection)
Connects different networks (LAN → WAN → Internet)
Divides broadcast domains
Runs routing protocols (RIP, OSPF, BGP)

Key point: Moves packets between networks.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Layer-3 Switch (Multilayer Switch)

OSI Layer: Layer 2 + Layer 3

What it does:
Works as a switch (MAC based switching)
AND as a router (IP routing)
Used in enterprise LANs
Faster than normal routers (ASIC-based routing)
-------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Access Point (Wireless AP)

OSI Layer: Layer 2 – Data Link

What it does:
Connects wireless devices to wired network
Works like a wireless switch
Uses 802.11 protocol
Key point: Converts Wi-Fi ↔ Ethernet.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Modem (Modulator/Demodulator)
OSI Layer: Layer 1 – Physical

What it does:
Converts analog ↔ digital signals
Used for DSL, Cable, and Fiber links
Connects home network to ISP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Firewall

OSI Layer:
Traditionally Layer 3 & Layer 4
Modern NGFW (Next-Gen): Layer 3–7

What it does:
Filters traffic (IP, Port, Protocol)
Protects networks
Can inspect packets deeply (Layer 7 filtering)
--------------------------------------------------------------
10. Gateway
OSI Layer: Layer 4–7 (varies by implementation)

What it does:
Connects different types of networks
Usually your home router is a gateway
Translates protocols (VoIP, email, etc.)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. NIC – Network Interface Card
OSI Layer: Layer 1 & Layer 2
What it does:
Physical connection to network
Has the MAC address
Converts data to signals
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
12. Load Balancer
OSI Layer:
Layer 4 (TCP-based load balancing)
Layer 7 (Application-level load balancing)

What it does:
Distributes traffic across servers
Used in web servers, APIs, cloud systems
